Problem 1: Beauty, or not, in the classroom

Part A

profs_ggplot <- ggplot(profs)
profs_ggplot + 
  geom_histogram(aes(x=eval), bins=20,  col='black',fill='dark red') + 
  theme_classic() + 
  labs(title='Distribution of Course Evaluation Scores', x='Course Evaluation Scores', y='Frequency')

Above is the distribution of the instructor’s average teaching evaluation score for courses in the sample. The distribution is negatively skewed, suggesting that more average scores tend to be larger than the mean.

Part B

ggplot(profs, aes(x = native, y = eval, fill = native)) + 
  geom_boxplot() + 
  labs(title='Course Evaluation Scores and Native English Speakers',
       x='Native English Speaker?', 
       y= 'Course Evaluation Scores') +
  theme_classic()

Above are the boxplots for professor’s average course evaluation scores by whether or not they are a native English speaker. It appears that native English speaking professors have higher average evaluations by students.

Part C

ggplot(profs, aes(x=eval))+
  geom_histogram(col='black',fill="dark green", bins= 15)+
  facet_wrap(~gender, ncol=1)+
  labs(title='Course Evaluation Scores by Gender',
       x='Evaluation Score', 
       y= 'Frequency')

Above are the distributions of average course evaluation scores by gender. The graph shows that male professors’ scores are more negatively skewed than those of the female professors, indicating more higher scores for the male professors.

Part D

profs_ggplot + 
  geom_point(aes(x=beauty, y=eval))+ 
  labs(title="Professor's Attractiveness vs. Course Evaluation Scores", 
       x='Physical Attractiveness',
       y='Course Evaluation Score') + 
  theme_classic()

The above scatterplot visualizes the relationship between professors’ physical attractiveness and their evaluation scores. With a correlation of 0.19, it is highly unlikely that there is a significant relationship between these two variables.
